Vheadline
p2
VYoung vocalist impresses
p3
sVnews
p4
VSujanaranjani held the vocal concert of Kaushik Kiran at Saptaparni. Kaushik hails from the family of musicians, being the grandson of renowned vocalist -violinist and scholar late Nallan Chakravartula Krishnamacharyulu whose reputation walked ahead of him in his days. The programme also brought into picture Krishnamacharyulu's son and Kaushik's father Buchayyacharyulu also a vocalist-violinist like his father. He accompanied his son Kaushik on violin. K.Rajagopalachari was on mridangam.Twenty-two-year-oldKaushik, an upcoming vocalist, began with Begada varnam, Intachalamu in adi talam of Sri Veena Kuppa Iyer. This was followed by Gana Nayakam in Malhari, written and composed by his father N.Ch. Buchaiayyacharyulu. Then, he rendered a composition of legendary musician, his grandfather, N.Ch. Krishnamacharyulu - Paramarthamide set in Keeravani, in Adi talam- modelled after Pancharatna Kirthanas of Thyagaraja, with swaram matching the sahithyam. It is a rare composition. Kaushik then rendered Govardhana Gireesam of Dikshitar in Hindolam and followed it with Sitapathe Naa Mansuna in Khamas of Thyagaraja.Kaushik then chose Latangi as his first raga essay of the concert for Marivere of Patnam. The kriti rendition was followed by swarakalpana. Popular Nagumomu in Abheri was his next number. Thodi was the main raga of the concert for Kaddanuvariki of Thyagaraja. Kaushik's father Buchaiayyacharylu also treated the raga extensively on his violin. Mridangam player followed it with Tani avarthanam. There was an Annamayya composition also, set in Ravichandrika composed by the violinist Buchaiayyacharyulu. Kaushik concluded the concert with a Thillana in Dhanasree of Swathi Thirunal.
